The bone house is still fascinated after 100 years. Take a look in Gaudi's interiors.
The roof resembles the back of a prehistoric saur, the staircase to a dinosaur spine and balconies to open fish mouths.
The Casa Battlo house in Barcelona is the architect Antoni Gaudi.
Because of its organic forms, the house was given the nickname of the Bone House.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stones, fragments of tiles and mosaics, facade reminiscent of scales and everywhere present curves, this is all that is ypic for the Art Nouveau by Antoni Gaudi.
The frontal facade of the house unrolls its dream lines, pleasant colors and textures reminiscent of nature and animals.
In the course of a more detailed observation, the geometry, the rhythm and the order designed with precision.
During the night the facade of the house becomes even more dramatic and is lit in such a way that the impression of brightness of the colors is reinforced.
The winding and the twist of the shapes also appears in the interiors with the same measurement.
Wood is a wave copy of window frames, balustrades, decorative elements of doors, eyelet and lamellae.
The Battlo house which stands in the Eixample district in the merchant street Passeig de Gracia at the number. 43, was born from the construction of a house in 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
Reconstruction took place for two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, Joseph Battlo, a wealthy entrepreneur, first insisted on the demolition of the old construction and the construction of another brand new but soon accepted Gaudi's idea of unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
But Casa Battlo's idea as a multi-family house was not thought of by Gaudi alone.
The architect Josep Maria Jujol worked with him.
It was precisely on his project that the decorations for a representation apartment of the owner of the building and the use of the mosaic for the facade were born.
For the facade also worked on other artists and creators.
The joint work for the Casa Battlo house plans began with successful cooperation between Jujol and Gaudi.
Jujol participated in the construction of the house of Gaudi Casa Mila and the Guell Park in which there are other works by Gaudi.
The locals nicknamed the house hot just after it was finished because of its organic forms "the bone house".
Others, given the specific mechanism for opening windows, have called it the "silk house".
It is said that at the top of the construction there is a sword similar to that of Saint George the patron of Catalonia.
Other sculpture elements of the construction contain hidden religious motifs.
Gaudi thought of the house as a unique system of central heating, with typical ventilation vents and chimneys.
Their 45-degree inclination sounds weird.
During the creation of Gaudi, it did not comply with the construction guidelines of the time at the time and was not hindered by them.
At the beginning of the construction he obtained the building permit from the city, knowing, of course, that the data on the reconstruction plans were so vague that two years after the finishing the city council was horrified and asked for modifications.
It was not pleasing, for example, to the members of the municipal council that the pillars of the construction encroach on the public sidewalk.
There was never any change, but, on the contrary, only 15 days after the call of the town Josep Battlo requested (and obtained satisfaction) permission to lease the two highest floors.
The owner moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a common lounge and in the third room a bedroom and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey house is shared by a staircase through which one accesses to an independent roof terrace.
All right angles and straight lines were cancelled by the basic elements of the reconstruction and their replacement by curved walls.
Gaudi also worked on the modern concept of connecting spaces.
The common part can be fully connected by opening the doors of the living rooms and high society can communicate comfortably or limit themselves to the private space for more intimate maintenance.
The house with the reconstruction of Gaudi received in addition to new facades a non-traditional roof and two more floors.
Gaudi's game with light is also impressive, blue and white glazed tiles with which the inner courtyard is decorated and with the skylights.
The two-color game gives maximum light in all floors of the house.
It was enough simply to bet on the principle that white should reflect more than the dark, which on the contrary absorbs the rays of the sun.
The Casa Battlo house, which was listed in 2005 as a UNESCO World Heritage Site, can be visited by everyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and splendid apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to take this step in 2002 on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
They continued the visits because they found that it was a lucrative business and they extended the scope of visits to common areas and the attic, including roof terraces.
The entrance ticket to the monument is really cheap and costs EUR 1650; students, pensioners, groups and tourist card holders have a 20% discount.
The sum is still above the price of entry into Gaudi's other buildings in the city.
If you want to feel the real atmosphere of the house with its fantastic turrets, you must quickly find a comrade among the inhabitants of the building and visit the house completely.
