Devices to follow people are increasingly in demand by parents who want to monitor their children.
Fear for their child leads more and more people to think about monitoring them through GPS.
The system, originally set up to search for cars, may as well be used to trace the movement of people and help in some cases as e.g. the model of little Anicka Janatkova.
The instrument is currently as big as a matchbox but will soon be the size of a watch.
The case of little Anicka has moved a large number of people and they have begun to look for ways to better protect their children.
Even if the price is to disrupt their privacy.
'We are trying to tell everyone that this is not something of espionage but only another way to reduce the likelihood of there being another tragedy,' says Petr Pilin of MAcro Weil, who is one of the suppliers of tracing devices on the Czech market.
"I admit that there may be cases of misuse of such appliances, such as putting it in the bags of a person who is not aware of it, but I have not yet encountered such cases."
'The majority of people are customers who actually buy the product for safety reasons,' adds Pilin.
In his view, children should always know for what purpose "the box" is used and how to use it in an emergency.
The child psychologist, Dana Bockova, draws attention that if the child does not want to carry something like this, he will get rid of it.
'And even the smallest can show great creativity when it comes to getting rid of something on purpose when they don't want to be under control.'
'Mobile phones, which can be cut like these tracing devices, have already brought parents to long expectations,' says Bockova.
In her view, the fact that such devices could help in the event of aggression was highly questionable.
"If it is a prepared abduction, the author will do everything possible to ensure that the child does not have an electronic device that can locate him".
"At the moment, it's the phone."
'As soon as tracing equipment develops, they (the criminals) will also look for them because the sale will be supported by an advertising campaign.'
'In such cases, criminals will always be ahead of the police,' says the psychologist.
She nevertheless confesses that such devices can help with an unprepared assault by a paedophile.
According to Robert Cech of RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both cars and people, claims that having such devices can help, even if it is destroyed in the case of an assault.
"The apparatus may be parameterized in such a way that it is in regular transmission after a determined period".
"In the event that the apparatus is destroyed, the last position of the person concerned remains".
'More expensive devices also have an inclinometer that immediately signals the position of the person who has slipped and is in a lying position without moving,' says Cech.
According to him, so-called intelligent mobile phones, which are equipped with a navigation system, can offer a comparable service after formatting it with special software.
The problem with current tracking systems is that it is either a device similar to those worn as a pendant the size of a matchbox or to the smallest telephone devices.
You can always lose them.
According to Pilina from Macro Weil, this is why tests are currently being carried out to make devices that look like common digital watches.
"This will have the advantage that the aggressor, if any, will not be able to recognise the tracing device".
'Or he will realize it after a while, which will have given the police a little more time,' he adds.
Whether the tracing device is developed in the form of a bracelet or pendant, it will always use the same technology as to trace cars.
