A longer index than the ring finger is a sign of low risk of cancer
Men who have older index fingers than the ring finger are at lower risk of having prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday by the British magazine Cancer.
This may depend on the level of the male hormone testosterone.
'Our findings show that the relative length of the finger serves as a simple test of the risk of prostate cancer, especially for men before the age of 60,' said co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, in particular by combining with genetic risk or other aggravating factors such as family health antecedents, Eeles added.
During the period 1994-2009 she followed with her colleagues in Britain more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time nearly 3,000 healthy men.
More than half of the participants in the study had the index of the right hand shorter than the ring finger.
For them, as for the 19 percent of those with their fingers of the same length, the same probability of prostate cancer was found.
In the case of those with the older index than the ring finger, however, the risk fell to 33 per cent, for men before the age of 60 the reduction in risk reached 87 per cent.
The ratio of length of the two fingers mentioned - formed during the prenatal period - indicates in particular different levels of sex hormones to which the child is exposed in the uterus.
A longer index is less testosterone.
Previous research had shown that testosterone helped develop prostate cancer.
Professor Vacla Paces, a renowned Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, said for CTK that he is aware of this study but that he does not seem to him to be the relationship between finger length and cancer to be "completely demonstrated".
