The discovery of a strange bacterium, which can use arsenic as one of its nutrients, expands the field to find new forms of life on Earth and perhaps beyond.
Although the researchers discovered the unusual bacterium here on Earth, they say this shows that life has possibilities beyond the major elements that have been considered essential.
"This body has a double capacity."
"It can grow either with phosphorus or with arsenic."
"That's why it's very special, even though it's far from being a really 'foreign' form of life," commented Paul Davies C. W. of the Arizona State University, co-author of the report in the Science newspaper's Thursday online edition.
Six major elements have long been considered essential for life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulphur.
But the researchers found that the bacterium, discovered in Lake Mono, California, is able to continue growing after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
"We wonder what's still possible," said Ariel Anbar D. of Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
Discovery is important when looking for life beyond Earth because researchers need to be able to recognize life, to know what life looks like, says Anbar.
The study focuses on a microbe found on Earth.
However, the announcement of a press conference to discuss it, which did not divulge the details of the find, generated widespread speculation on the Internet that the report might divulge the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
This was not the case.
The discovery 'shows that, in other planetary environments, organisms may be able to use other elements to actuate biochemistry and that the 'standard' set of elements, which we consider absolutely necessary for life, may not be fixed,' commented Charles Cockell, Professor at the Institute of Planetary and Space Scientific Research, Open University, Milton Keynes, United Kingdom.
Cockell was not part of the research team.
'This work is new because it shows the substitution of one element to another in fundamental biochemistry and biochemical structure,' added Cockell.
It was not a fortuitous discovery.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of the NASA Institute of Astrology, which led the study, chose Lake Mono because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar; for example, it has speculated that a microbe exposed to the two substances may be able to substitute for each other.
"Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is really similar to that of phosphorus."
'As a result, it is difficult for agencies to distinguish these elements separately.'
'But arsenic is different enough that it doesn't work exactly like phosphorus; it gets inside and, somehow, erases the work of our biochemical machine,' explained Anbar.
Researchers collected the bacterium known as GFAJ-1 and exposed it to increasing concentrations of arsenic to which it was able to adapt and grow.
The microbe grows better with phosphorus, but the fact that it can live with arsenic instead raises the possibility that an arsenic-using life form may occur naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, an assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said that the idea that arsenic could be replaced by phosphorus was not new; but nothing ever showed that it could work.
Arsenic was more common at the beginning of the Earth's existence; she says; for example, researchers hypothesized that early life could have used it.
This suggests that there might be other ways to form life, not just the way life on Earth was formed at the beginning,' said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was funded by NASA, the Ministry of Energy and the National Institute of Health.
