After a campaign of invective and negativity, a modicum of civility erupted in Washington this week.
Is this a harbinger of genuine forward forward bipartisan cooperation or an illusory moment before the rapid return to partisan struggle in the capital?
Tuesday's meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders produced no breakthroughs on the major issues that need to be addressed during the "laudy duck" session.
But obviously, there was at least a polite discussion about the differences between the two sides as well as the recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another episode where each side wanted to score points.
Wednesday's public meeting of the committee on the President's deficit was just as civilised, despite the remaining political differences between the members.
It seems clear that the close interaction of several months has created mutual respect that transcends the ideological gap; but which, however, still divides the members.
It is barely enough to declare a new era of cooperation.
Both sides are now in a period of trial and mutual testing with a view to obtaining signs of cooperation and compromise, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters for a renewed partisan war.
For this reason, Tuesday's meeting and subsequent comments from participants revealed a minimum of demands or charges.
The philosophical differences between Obama and Republicans are too large and too deep to suggest a rapid climate change that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it is taxation, expenditure, health care or rights, both parties remain miles away.
Yet the November election had moderated Washington, at least in the short term.
"There is no doubt that things have changed in the tone," said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official, now next to the Center for Ethical and Public Policy.
"This is inevitable after the elections.
The elections are a source of partisan and then fading.
That's good."
On some issues, including those on the agenda of the "lush duck" session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush’s tax cuts will expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favour of that.
Both sides want to find a way to preserve some or all of them, either permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, a compromise is conceivable on extending unemployment benefits, if only because Republicans cannot afford to give the impression that they are in favour of tax cuts for the rich, while at the same time denying unemployment benefits to unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's meeting at the White House, more optimism is hanging out for possible agreement on the issues raised during the session on "laughing duck", with the ratification of the New START pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warned that fruitful cooperation on the most pressing issues of the "Duck" session did not necessarily lead to a better understanding between the two parties when the 112th Congress met in January.
Instead, he says, a period of disagreement is likely, if not inevitable.
'Once the things that need to be done are, psychology in the short term will return to one of the confrontations,' he said.
Wehner also expressed his widely shared scepticism that civility would lead to genuine cooperation.
"I consider most of what happens between today and 2012 as a pre-show or shadow boxing compared to the main event of 2012, he said.
The reasons for this are closely related to the composition of the new Republican majority in the House and to the tea voters who contributed to its creation.
But Republican leaders are aware of the dangers if they go too far, they know that they must try to live up to their promises to cut public spending and repeal the new health-care law.
These partisan positions are already clear in the initial reactions to the deficit committee's recommendations, which include reforming the tax code and raising certain taxes, raising the retirement age and reducing spending.
Co-Presidents Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles chose one of the most difficult tasks in Washington and, in themselves, imposed the deficit on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member committee to make their plan as a formal recommendation, and they have found it difficult to reach that number.
There is still the greatest resistance among the elected representatives of the group, which suggests that there are on tax issues, at least today, few motives or willingness to compromise.
Galston planned two phases in the fighting between the White House and the congressional Republicans.
The first will come next year in the form of partisan confrontations, given that Republicans challenge Obama in terms of budget, taxes, and health care; and then followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would be the cause of the change?
Public opinion.
There is ample evidence that, despite the spirit of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want the two parties to work together.
If confrontation leads to a stalemate, as in 1995, then both parties will closely observe the public reaction.
Anyone who is deemed to be losing will have to change course and find compromises.
But that would be an optimistic view.
The partisan mind and polarization are bigger today than they were in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a larger ideological gap between Obama and congressional Republicans than there were between President Bill Clinton and Republicans at the time.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as a mere prelude to a larger election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civility exposed this week could be appreciated by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
