The European Union changes the rules for obtaining a visa
Individuals must attend Visa Applicant Service Centres prior to their interview in the Consular Section; the cost of the waiting time will be reduced.
From 10 January 2011, the visa processing procedure at the United States Embassy and Consulates will change.
Under the new procedure, the majority of applicants will be required to report to the Visa Applicant Service Centres (ASC, according to their abbreviations in English) prior to their interview in the Consular Section.
CSA staff will take the biometric information of the applicant, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have some advantages for aspirants, including the following:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, it will no longer be necessary to make a payment to obtain an appointment, another payment for the processing of the visa and another for the mail service to deliver the document.
The aspirant will make a single payment that will cover all three services.
The current fare will remain the same: the equivalent of 140 dollars for a tourist visa, 150 dollars in the case of applications visas (includes visas for temporary workers) and 390 dollars for merchant and investor visas.
Those who wish to renew their visa should not appear in an interview with the Consular Representative, they will only report to the nearest ASC where they will present the documents and take their fingerprints.
Because biometric information will be taken from the CSA, applicants who wish to have a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will be less time-consuming than before.
Similarly, visa applicants to the Consulates of Ciudad Juarez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra-service rate of 26 dollars.
For more information on the new visa procedure, visit http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201-Visas-FAQs.html
