A global plan to renovate lighting
Yesterday in Cancun, the United Nations proposed a plan to renovate domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries with a view to achieving a reduction in greenhouse gases (GHGs) that corresponds to almost one third of the additional reduction that needs to be achieved in order to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is in the wake of the major concrete projects that the United Nations hopes to have adopted in Cancun to compensate for the lack of binding commitments to reduce by the industrialized countries.
According to the plan tabled yesterday, if the incandescent light bulbs that still monopolize 50-70% of the market were replaced by compact fluorescent light bulbs or, better still, by light-emitting diode (LED) bulbs, the bulk of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of GHGs emitted over the planet to lighten humans would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This is equivalent to 70% of the emissions of the global fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitting countries, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, embarked on voluntary reduction plans that are expected to increase overall GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will be necessary to subtract from this still 5 Gt balance sheet to stabilize by 2020 the increase in the climate at 2 degrees centigrade in order to prevent it from becoming out of control.
In incandescent light bulbs, 95% of the energy dissipates in the form of heat and the rest, i.e. 5%, produces light.
With compact fluorescent light bulbs, the energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, this need for energy is reduced by two more times.
Compact fluorescent light bulbs last on average from 6000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED light bulbs, such as those launched by the Philips manufacturer this week - this company participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent light bulb, which gives an idea of the economy with a replacement plan that would apply to 100 countries.
These brand new light bulbs can also work with rheostats in addition to emitting very little heat.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several experts have had reservations about CFLs as they contain mercury and need to be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless manufacturers are issuing instructions.
But, according to the report, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the CFL, but rather coal-fired thermal power plants, which emit a lot of mercury to produce wasted electricity in incandescent light bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report details the gains that each country would make through this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save one billion dollars a year in electricity purchases and eight million tons of CO2, equivalent to 3.5 thermal power plants that would cost it 2.5 billion dollars.
