In addition, minced steak, canned tuna, and even bread stick and chewing gum were full of pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water, analyses revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
For dinner, salmon steak was the most "rich" with 34 chemical residues detected and even the examination of the plastic plate used to warm the meal in the microwave was not free of it.
The final risk to the consumer of this 'contaminant cocktails' is probably underestimated, according to the study.
The Europe Ecology-Greens/Greens Alliance (EE-LV), for its part, has proposed 'facilitated urgency' to introduce a moratorium on the use of pesticides, in order to stop 'the increase in diseases of civilisation'.
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) reported residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, 76 of them in cereals.
